      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink font-sans mb-6">Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) Overtime Pay Policies & Calculations</h2>
      <div class="text-body text-sm md:text-base font-sans leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>
          Understanding overtime regulations is critical for protecting employee rights and ensuring compliance. The primary federal policy governing working hours is the **Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA)**, which mandates overtime compensation thresholds.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Calculating Regular and Overtime Hours</h3>
        <p>
          Federal guidelines specify that any work hours exceeding **40 hours in a single 168-hour workweek** are classified as overtime hours. Under the FLSA, non-exempt workers must be paid an overtime rate of at least **1.5 times** their regular rate of pay.
          <br />
          Consider our verification test case:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-3 font-sans text-sm">
          <li><strong>Hourly Rate:</strong> $20.00 per hour</li>
          <li><strong>Total Hours Worked:</strong> 45 hours (40 regular hours + 5 overtime hours)</li>
          <li><strong>Regular Pay:</strong> $40 \times \$20 = \$800.00$</li>
          <li><strong>Overtime Pay Rate:</strong> $\$20 \times 1.5 = \$30.00$</li>
          <li><strong>Overtime Pay:</strong> $5 \times \$30.00 = \$150.00$</li>
          <li><strong>Total Pay:</strong> $\$800.00 + \$150.00 = \$950.00$</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">State-Specific Double-Time Rules</h3>
        <p>
          While federal guidelines do not enforce double-time (2.0x regular rate) pay, certain jurisdictions impose additional guidelines:
          <br />
          In **California**, employers must pay double-time rates for all hours worked past 12 in a single workday, or past 8 hours on the seventh consecutive day of work in a single workweek.
        </p>
      
<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Understanding FLSA Rules on Exempt vs. Non-Exempt Employees</h3>
        <p>
          The Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) regulates overtime eligibility in the United States. Employees are divided into two classifications: exempt and non-exempt. Non-exempt employees are legally entitled to receive overtime pay (1.5 times their regular hourly rate) for all hours worked over 40 in a workweek. Exempt employees, who are typically salaried professionals, executives, or administrators earning above a set weekly salary threshold, are excluded from overtime protections. Misclassifying non-exempt workers as exempt to avoid paying overtime is a common FLSA violation that can result in significant legal penalties and back-pay requirements.
        </p>
        <p>
          Additionally, regular rate calculations must include non-discretionary bonuses and commissions. If a worker receives an hourly bonus, that bonus must be factored into their base rate before calculating overtime, which is a common calculation error.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Scenario: Standard Weekly Overtime Math</h3>
        <p>
          Let's walk through how overtime is calculated for a standard workweek. Suppose an employee earns a base rate of $20 per hour and works 48 hours in a single week.
        </p>
        <p>
          First, calculate regular earnings for the first 40 hours: <code>40 hours &times; $20 = $800</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, identify the overtime hours worked: <code>48 total hours - 40 regular hours = 8 overtime hours</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Calculate the overtime pay rate (time-and-a-half): <code>$20 &times; 1.5 = $30</code> per hour.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multiply the overtime rate by the overtime hours: <code>8 hours &times; $30 = $240</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sum the regular and overtime pay to find the total gross earnings: <code>$800 + $240 = $1,040</code>. Our overtime calculator handles this math instantly, helping you verify timesheet accuracy.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">State-Level Overtime Guidelines and Daily Overtime Rules</h3>
        <p>
          While federal law calculates overtime solely on a weekly basis, several states have established daily overtime rules that provide additional protections. In California, for example, non-exempt employees must receive time-and-a-half pay for hours worked over 8 in a single workday, and double-time pay for hours worked over 12. Additionally, working seven consecutive days in a single workweek triggers overtime requirements for the first 8 hours on the seventh day. Always verify your state's labor laws to ensure compliance.
        </p>        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink font-sans mt-8 mb-3">Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) Overtime Pay Rules</h3>
        <p>
          Under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), covered nonexempt employees must receive overtime pay for hours worked over 40 per workweek. The minimum overtime rate is one and one-half times the employee's regular hourly pay rate. The FLSA does not require overtime pay for work on weekends, holidays, or regular rest days unless those hours exceed the 40-hour limit. Understanding these federal guidelines is crucial for verifying that your paystub calculations match standard legal requirements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

